Introduction

Quote from an article in the MIT Technology Review by Manuel Castells:

“The Internet is the decisive technology of the Information Age, and with the explosion of wireless communication in the early twenty-first century, we can say that humankind is now almost entirely connected, albeit with great levels of inequality in bandwidth, efficiency, and price.”

  • Conduct extensive analysis using data from CIA World Factbook and the democracy index developed by the Economist Intelligence Unit.

Objectives

We aim to investigate the following details:

  1. Define our methods as to how internet usage is measured in a country, and base our analysis on them.

  2. Examine and analyze the difference, as defined by our group, in internet usage in each country.

  3. Examine and analyze the impact of democracy, education, economy, and health, as defined by our group, on internet usage, as defined by our group.

What defines Internet Access?

Data Overview

Problem Definition

Metric for “Internet Access”

We define the quality of the Internet access of a country based on 2 main criterion:

  1. The amount/proportion of the population having Internet access \[\text{InternetUserProp}=\frac{\text{InternetUsers}}{\text{Population}}\]

  2. The quality (congested ness) of Internet access (i.e.worse when one connection is shared between many people) \[\text{PersonPerBroadband}=\frac{\text{InternetUsers}}{\text{Broadband}}\]

These can be computed with the existing data.

Initial Observations

After computing the 2 variables, we can plot them on a scatter-plot. On which, we attempt to find patterns (clusters) of the state of the country.

Country Classifications

We can divide the countries into 3 segments:

  1. Countries with small internet reach with resources shared among more people

    Definition: \(\text{InternetUserProp} < 0.5\) and \(\text{PersonPerBroadband} \geq 75\)

  2. Countries with small internet reach, but has relatively private/good access

    Definition: \(\text{InternetUserProp} < 0.5\) and \(\text{PersonPerBroadband} < 75\)

  3. Countries with large reach while having private/good access

    Definition: \(\text{InternetUserProp} \geq 0.5\)

Metrics for Further Analysis

Continuous Metrics

We use InternetUserProp and PersonPerBroadband as continuous metrics, used in linear regression.

Discrete Metrics

With QualityClass, we can divide the countries into segments, and observe the situation more qualitatively.

Conclusion

  • Objective: Examine and analyze differences in internet access and quality around the world.

  • Breadth and quality of Internet access varies greatly by region.

  • Democracy impacts the internet use of a country but education does not.

  • Positive correlation between GDP Per Capita and Life Expectancy with internet usage.

Possible Future Investigations

  1. Does Internet access propel democracy, or is it the other way around?

  2. Is there a shift of educatedness of Internet users over time?

  3. Do the 4 factors introduced exist as possible solutions to increase Internet access?
